{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dc301939-b7f7-476f-a25b-eb076c5e78f8","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request** — each request automatically gets its own scope. In **MAUI, there's no per-request scope**. The app has a single scope for its entire lifetime, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your DbContext lives forever, accumulating tracked entities across navigations.\n\n**Fixes (pick one):**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — simplest; new DbContext per injection:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Create manual scopes** via `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Clear the change tracker** when navigating:\n   ```csharp\n   dbContext.ChangeTracker.Clear();\n   ```\n\nOption 1 is the most common approach. Option 2 gives you explicit lifetime control similar to ASP.NET Core's per-request model.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"88946698-ede9-4788-b4ab-5bd4bb45117d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping — specifically why `AddScoped` behaves differently in MAUI than in ASP.NET Core.\n\nThis is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request — each request gets its own scope, so each request gets a fresh DbContext.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, there is no per-request scope. The DI container in MAUI has a single scope for the entire application lifetime. \n\nSo `AddScoped` effectively becomes `AddSingleton` — you end up with one DbContext instance that persists across the entire app, causing tracked entities to accumulate unexpectedly as you navigate between pages. The solution is to either switch to `AddTransient` for fresh instances each time, manually manage scopes with `IServiceScopeFactory`, or explicitly clear the change tracker when needed.","outputTokens":568,"requestId":"B7CD:28DDBA:176737:1EA0A5:69FFDA24"},"id":"aceaac33-80cd-40a0-b11b-50e378dab55f","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:06:56.787Z","parentId":"c8d22e5f-5a7b-488b-92e7-88c9086191b1"}
